            alt="Reading cover" />

        <!-- Content -->
        <article class="prose prose-lg max-w-none prose-headings:font-bold prose-a:text-cyan-600">

            <p>
                Semantic HTML is the foundation of accessible, maintainable, and SEO-friendly web applications.
                In this lesson, you'll learn why semantic elements matter and how to use them effectively.
            </p>

            <h2>What is Semantic HTML?</h2>

            <p>
                Semantic HTML elements clearly describe their meaning to both the browser and the developer.
                Examples include <code>&lt;header&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;nav&gt;</code>,
                <code>&lt;main&gt;</code>, and <code>&lt;footer&gt;</code>.
            </p>

            <blockquote>
                “Semantic HTML is not optional. It’s the backbone of accessibility.”
            </blockquote>

            <h2>Why It Matters</h2>

            <ul>
                <li>Improves accessibility for screen readers</li>
                <li>Makes code easier to maintain</li>
                <li>Enhances SEO</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Example</h2>

            <pre><code>&lt;article&gt;
  &lt;header&gt;
    &lt;h1&gt;Blog title&lt;/h1&gt;
  &lt;/header&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Content...&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/article&gt;
</code></pre>

            <p>
                In the next lesson, you’ll apply semantic HTML to a real layout.
            </p>

        </article>

